Introduction
1.1 Background
With the emergence of COVID-19 Pandemic, one of the biggest concerns for people is having to
touch public places. As medical professionals suggest, we should avoid contact with direct and
indirect contact with contaminated objects or surfaces, the virus can live up to 3 days and be
transported through metal surfaces. Also recommended by medical professionals, is that masks
greatly reduce the contamination rate of COVID-19. Therefore, if we assist companies in the
effort to reduce physical contact and require masks upon entry, we can reduce the risk of
COVID-19 to staff and customers. In the world of IT, we automate to make our lives easier.
Hence, an automated door opening system is thought to reduce possible transmission of
contacting public surfaces.
1.2

Purpose
The purpose of this document is to convey the requirement of the proposed RFID mask system,
providing guidelines for the application configuration and associated components in terms of
design, interface, process, and tracings related architectures. It describes framework, quality
standard as well as artifacts that are needed to guide through system construction. This
document provides information on the procedures that are necessary for the system
completeness and accuracy, including information required to effectively manage RFID Mask
System from planning to delivery.
1.3

Goals
The goal of the automated door opening system is to reduce the need of people touching
contaminated public surfaces. By implementing sensors, specifically RFID sensors, at public
entrances, which detects whether or not a person is wearing a mask. The entrance door will
automatically open upon detection of a person with a valid mask on, therefore reducing the need
of touching contaminated public surfaces and chance of spreading COVID-19.
1.4

Scope Overview
Our Automatic door opener is a system that uses RFID mask sensors to open doors upon
detection of masks worn on a person's face. The idea came to light from the need of protective
masks when entering a building/company. The system is composed of a RFID sensor placed at
the building’s entrance that detects an employee/guest identity through the RFID chipped mask.
A monitoring system with interfaces will also be deployed for system administrator managing
guest entrance. Functions of the monitoring system composed of video view of the entrance
status, auditing function tracking people enter/exit the building and manually blocking doors from
opening when a suspicious person is seen.

Terms & Definition
3
RFID
Radio-frequency identification uses electromagnetic fields to
automatically identify and track tags attached to objects. An
RFID tag consists of a tiny radio transponder; a radio receiver
and transmitter
Sensor
A device whose purpose is to detect events or changes in its
environment and send the information to other electronic
Auditing
Logical process that determine the information systems of
detailed information technology processes, controls and
activities, enables purpose of security through tracking
Requirements
2.1

Functional Requirement
The functional requirements are specified by how the system must be able to perform, including
the behavior and workflow and features of the door opening system. The constraints of the
system in terms of functional usage are outlined in bullet points as following:
- The door itself must have a compatible scanner that works with the RFID mask
- Once users are verified by mask, the doors open
- The system must compose management system for monitoring
- The system must be audited to keep track of user entrance
- The system reject door from opening if user does not have mask
- The management system must be monitored by IT administrator
- The management system must only allow access for authenticated user
- The management system must compose of user interface
- The management must know if a user accessed the door without a mask on
- The management system must display camera image, mask ID and menu options
- The management system must offer technical help assistance for employees who have
issue with RFID (exp: stopped working, replacement) or the sensor
2.2

Non-Functional Requirement
The non-functional requirement captures the project properties and attributes that verify the
performance of the automatic door opening system. These define the user needs and experience,
maintaining consistency throughout the system. Listing are indicated in bullet points shown as
following:
- Each door opening request detected by sensor should be processed within 10 seconds
- The system is composed of security implementation
- The system must be active during business hours and inactive during closed hours
- The system is reading individual RFID when group of people are detected
- The management system must timeout and lock itself after period of inactivity
- The management system command such as manual open and close the door should
have a latency of no greater than 30 seconds
- The RFID sensor capable of detection within 10 feet despite weather condition
- All auditing transcript and video recording should all be backed up at daily bases
- The sensor detects people at door entrance
- The RFID can be removed from the mask so the person can wash/dispose the mask
4
2.3

User Experience Requirement
The goal is to meet the exact need of the user, encompassing all aspects of the end user
interaction with the automatic door opening service. Building the reputation for the system by
covering system usability and efficiency:
- The graphical user interface for management system should be clearly designed for user
navigation
- The physical devices such as sensor should be placed on top of the door for mask
detection
- The physical environment (entrance gate) must be kept clean at all times (aka. free of
trash, site sterilization and free of trash)
- The door automatically opens upon detection of people
- Guest RFID Masks are provided at the entrance
5
Justifications & Mockup
3.1

General
The reasoning behind our project idea is to not only to enhance the safety of businesses but their
employees/customers as well. The biggest point for our project is that we wanted to create a safe
way for businesses to incorporate mandatory safety masks while reducing the need for physical
contact. Our project also reduces the amount of contact that is needed for one to enter the
building; whether it is physically touching the door or a need for a greeter checking if all masks
are being worn. The core of this idea is that the RFID mask sensor system works with automatic
doors, if the door sensor reads the RFID chip then it opens letting an authorized user in.
3.1

Mask Requirement
According to the CDC, masks are recommended as a barrier to prevent respiratory droplets from
spreading through air. The filter layer of masks has been proven effective in blocking COVID-19
virus from contacting human skin. Since COVID-19 can be spread by people who do not have
symptoms, social distance and wearing masks are good practices to reduce the chance of
spreading. A company building is a closed space with not only the employee but guests of
various people passing in and out at daily bases. Therefore, wearing mask is required to prevent
the spread of COVID-19
3.2

Sensor Positioning
As part of the non-functional requirement, RFID mask sensor is placed at top of the door where
users simply need lift head up for mask scanning. It is designed this way to incorporate people at
different heights. Sensor is meant to have a different color in contrast with the building, as well as
enlarged framing where users would easily identify the position of the sensor.
6
3.3

Mask Positioning
As part of the user experience requirement, guest masks are provided at the entrance with built-in
guest RFID, it’s designed for guests who wish to enter the building and employees who forgot
their mask. According to American Science Survey, 90% of the people are right-handed. Hence in
considering visibility and accessibility for the majority, the free mask station is positioned at the
right side of the entrance where people can grab masks easily.
3.4

RFID Chipped Mask
The RFIDs are meant to be built inside the mask at a position indicated by the blue dot, it would
match a person's cheek area without interfering with the nose and mouth area for breathing. The
mask and RFID structure are indicated below:

3.5

Unauthorized Access
Piggybacking has become a great problem for
unauthorized people attempting to enter the
building. Unlike hacking through networks,
unauthorized people who enter the building
puts the company at risk since these people
can pretend to be employees and gain physical
information as an “insider”. The system is
designed where doors will shut instantly after
entrance of authorized identity. All the RFIDs
and paired faces are tracked by the system, the
management system monitored by
administrator could also push “lock” button to
close the gate when suspicious person are
seen
3.6

Management System Interface
The interface for the monitoring system is shown below with its main purpose tracking people
entering/exiting the building. A front and back camera view shows the front and back of a person.
Since the management system is closely monitored by the administrator, the back view is for the
admin to identify if the person is hiding a suspicious weapon behind their back. The date and time
of the access serves as
part of the auditing
function, keeping record of
all visits that may or may
not be used for the future.
Failed access indicates
RFID chip malfunction or
sensor malfunction where
it would require the admin
manually open the gate
through the menu.
8
3.1.6

Auditing
All RFID indicated recordings should all be backed up at daily bases for security reasons. It keeps
the record of the company tracking criminals who attempt to steal company property. Video
recordings will help police ensuing investigation as well as tracking employee theft identified by
RFID.
Deployment
4.1

System Interfaces
The application management system resides on a server, connection to the internet is required to
interact with sensor, camera and management system.
a) Sensor sends RFID code to management system through internal network
b) Camera sends capture views to management system
c) The management system receives the RFID, process to store RFID with associated
camera view into database
4.2 Nodes
− Client RFID Chip
Client device is used to access the building through RFID reading and authentication
managed by the sensor system
− Administrative Device
Administrative device composed of physical machine connected to the internal company
network used to access RFID reading and camera view, authenticated for backup driver
storage, account management, database management and RFID tracking functions
− Storage Drive
The drive used to store all past auditing data serves the backup function.
− Database Server
The database server deploys MySQL works closely with the administrative device, providing
data appending and retrieving services to the management system. It is an open source
relational database management system that provides data organization
4.3

Connections
− Ethernet
The communication between sensor, camera and management devices is archived by
ethernet where data are transferred through internal company network
− JCBC
Database connectivity is the primary connection established between management system
and database in order to access MySQL library
9
Conclusion
Our design aimed to create a practical but safe automated way to track if persons/employees follow mask
mandates. Our design's goal was making our system simple for the user but enhancing the safety and
well-being of every company that implements our design. Implementation of RFID technology is simply
not only because most companies have automated door systems already but in the modern-day RFID
authentication is already widely used. Our technology also allows any company to authenticate and track
who is within their building/premises. With our current times safety is a priority for not companies but
people around the world. With our RFID mask system, we can help encourage and enhance the safety of
everyone.
